{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531835"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:19:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:19:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14633"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14633"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.15,0.03,0.31,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107899"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7326"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90316"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"3068"},{"type":"tags","id":"4020"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17886"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48049"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107899"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old man is admitted to hospital with worsening dysphagia. He has metastatic gastric cancer with peritoneal and liver metastases diagnosed six months ago. His medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and atrial fibrillation. His regular medications include modified-release morphine 60 mg twice daily, metformin, apixaban, and bisoprolol. He has been taking regular oral morphine for three months with good pain control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver the past 24 hours, he has developed complete dysphagia for tablets and can only manage small sips of fluid. He appears distressed and agitated. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 150/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. On examination, he is diaphoretic with dilated pupils, piloerection, and mild tremor. His abdomen is soft with mild generalised tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate long term analgesic option for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Buprenorphine sublingual tablet","Intravenous patient-controlled analgesia","Oral morphine solution","Continuous subcutaneous infusion of morphine","Transdermal fentanyl patch"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of opioid withdrawal after being unable to take his regular oral morphine due to dysphagia. The symptoms include agitation, tachycardia, hypertension, diaphoresis, dilated pupils, and piloerection. Given his stable opioid requirements and the underlying cause of his inability to take oral medications, conversion to an alternative route of administration is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransdermal fentanyl patch\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate long-term analgesic option for this patient. It provides continuous analgesia without requiring oral administration, making it ideal for patients with dysphagia. For a patient with stable pain control on oral morphine, a fentanyl patch offers a convenient and effective alternative. The appropriate dose would be calculated based on his current daily morphine dose of 120 mg, which would approximate to a 50 mcg/hour fentanyl patch. While patches take 24-72 hours to reach therapeutic levels, this can be managed by using short-term bridging analgesia during the transition period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous subcutaneous infusion of morphine\u003C/strong\u003E is an excellent short-term solution during hospitalisation and can be used as bridging therapy while waiting for the fentanyl patch to reach therapeutic levels. However, it is less practical as a long-term solution for a patient with advanced cancer, as it requires regular pump maintenance and healthcare provider involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral morphine solution\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate given the patient\u0027s dysphagia affects his ability to swallow both tablets and liquids safely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous patient-controlled analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessarily invasive for long-term management and would require ongoing intravenous access, limiting mobility and increasing the risk of complications such as infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBuprenorphine sublingual tablet\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as it may precipitate withdrawal in a patient who is currently opioid-dependent. Additionally, the partial agonist properties may provide inadequate analgesia compared to his previous full agonist opioid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen converting between different opioids, it is important to account for incomplete cross-tolerance by reducing the calculated equianalgesic dose by approximately 25-50% to prevent overdosage. Additional breakthrough analgesia should be prescribed, and the patient should be monitored closely during the conversion period. In practice, a continuous subcutaneous infusion would likely be used initially during hospitalisation to stabilize the patient\u0027s pain and withdrawal symptoms, with transition to the fentanyl patch for long-term management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid withdrawal can occur when regular opioids are stopped abruptly, including in patients unable to swallow oral medications.","Transdermal fentanyl patches are an appropriate alternative to oral opioids in patients with stable opioid requirements who cannot swallow.","The conversion ratio from oral morphine to transdermal fentanyl must account for incomplete cross-tolerance between different opioids."],"references":["Ahn JS, Lin J, Ogawa S, Yuan C, O\u2019Brien T, Le BH, Bothwell AM, Moon H, Hadjiat Y, Ganapathi A. Transdermal buprenorphine and fentanyl patches in cancer pain: a network systematic review. Journal of Pain Research. 2017 Aug 18:1963-72. Available online at ; https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.2147/JPR.S140320#d1e230","Faculty of Pain Medicine, Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists (ANZCA). PS01 (PM)-Appendix. Opioid dose equivalence conversion table 2021. Published June 2021 Faculty of Pain Medicine, ANZCA, VIC, Australia. Available online at ; https://www.anzca.edu.au/getattachment/6892fb13-47fc-446b-a7a2-11cdfe1c9902/PS01(PM)-(Appendix)-Opioid-Dose-Equivalence-Calculation-Table"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90316"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14633"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90316"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-04T13:54:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-04T13:57:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7326"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107899"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/251"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Gastric cancer","synonyms":["Stomach cancer","Stomach malignancy","Stomach tumour","Stomach malignacny","Gastric malignancy","Gastric tumour","Gastric mass"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22